I've been here over 20 times and tried most of the menu. Everything in excellent including the cocktails. They sometimes have special events like a pig roast that are also amazing.

We love Kiwiana. They have great food and a very friendly staff. We actually had our engagement brunch here and they printed custom menus for us and really made sure the meal went well, which of course it did! Highly recommend.

Great restaurant! Everything from the quality of the food to the presentation to the service to the amazing wine list. Definitely will be back.

Great unique and delicious food with very friendly and attentive staff. Some of the best Pavlova cake my dad has ever had, and an amazing selection of wine.  Eating here really feels like being in New Zealand. It's a must visit! Again and again!
Excellent food and hospitality
This place reminds me of home! Wonderfully creative brunch fare with New Zealand flair. And you can have Milo and Anzac biscuits!
Excellent service and food! Highly recommend!
Great service and delicious food! The scones are to die for!
Excellent food and service
We love coming here for light, creative dishes, and refreshing cocktails. Service is always very attentive and every dish I've tried, I haven't been disappointed.

Food was delicious (I had the salmon with artichoke at brunch), unbelievable scones, and fairly priced. Staff was nice and coffe was excellent too. It's cash only.
A refreshing culinary experience and excellent service in an affordable package. Highly recommended.

Food was okay, I will admit, but the racism of the staff was really unacceptable. Came in with a friend and we were treated so poorly and disrespectfully. I would not recommend this restaurant to anyone.

Bad service, started moping the floor around us while we were still eating brunch. They were supposed to close in 10 mins and we were the last customers. The food was nothing to write home about. Edit - for anyone reading the reviews please notice the owner reply to my comment. I noticed someone else complained the place was racist (if you scroll down the comments). Wonderful service and perfect food prepared by one of the most talented chefs in Brooklyn. We had platters of oysters followed by succulent lamb and delicious desserts. The perfect evening with friends!

I really wanted to love this place, but I'll settle for liking it. No, not all the dishes really work, but at least they're trying, which is more than I can say for most restaurants. The prices are also very agreeable.
Neighborhood favorite, never disappoints. Lamb chops are amazing, short rib is off the charts. Fantastic and unique spices. Fabulous wine & cocktails. Great for dinner and brunch.

Went there once with my dog so we sat outdoor. The server stepped on my dog for a few times without any apology, as if my dog was not a living thing....

An underappreciated neighborhood gem. Brunch is always popular, but dinner is also fantastic. If you're looking for a quiet spot with great food, this is excellent! Menu boasts favorites (like lamb chops and the fried chicken) as well as some seasonal choices. They also have a great private event space downstairs in the wine cellar.

The kiwi burger was delicious and the lamb as well. I tried the Boysenberry cider and it was sweet and yummy, also their warm fuzzy sweater drink was so sweet. The waitress was nice and quick with the service, would def come back!

Food was very good, fresh and healthy! Definitely lots of flavor and we got lucky with the $1 oysters which were amazing! Service was also good. Looking forward to trying their brunch.
Very little vibe and some food is inedible. I tried fettuccine with beetroot and Parmesan sauce and it was truly terrible. My date had ribs which was excellent, but I’d prefer more consistency.
Cute and lovely place to dine with a couple of friends. Saw people with kids here too. Friendly staffs and great food. Lucky to have such a restaurant in this neighborhood.
Very good food, great location. The owner was super friendly and provided great service.
Great service in a corset atmosphere, we went at New Years but the service was still fast and the food was on point! I would recommend it for sure, the portions are not small either.

Though the restaurant features fresh ingredients and a uniform team, the chef seems to be micromanaging his capable employees. He was bartender, expediter, waiter, and host when we were there, and the food came out slower than expected. The tater tots were good, but the beets salad lacked flavor.

We've been here twice and had a really lovely experience both times. The food manages to stand out as both comforting and innovative. Several dishes are twists on modern American (both North & South) classics. Chef Simmons personally provides a welcoming atmosphere, making this a neighborhood gem. In the winter the restaurant can get a bit chilly, so I recommend bringing a jacket or a flask. For dessert, the sticky date pudding is especially decadent. Overall, highly recommend.
Grate place , little  piece of New Zealand in NY
Chill atmosphere good food & great service!

Unique and delicious experience. This is the first New Zealand restaurant I’ve been to and the food was outstanding. I also discovered a white wine from New Zealand I’d never seen before and plan to purchase a case once I track down an importer.
So much fun to go to as a kiwi away from home
This place is simply not worth your time.  Nothing truly appalling, but there are better options available, and their particular iteration of New Zealand/Kiwi food is simply uninspired.
Great food and atmosphere. Been there several times. Never a disappointment.

Good cocktails, fantastic service. One in our party has dietary restrictions and they happily made an off-menu plate. The baby back ribs were incredibly tender. The fried chicken was a little overcooked but the sides were fantastic. If I'm in the neighborhood again, I'd gladly return.
Great spot with both comforting and unique food. The chef is knowledgeable and kind, the food is delicious.
Awesome dinner, the octopus salad was amazing!!

My brunch fare seemed pretty standard, I'm not sure if it had a New Zealand twist or not.  The potato hash it came with was different though. But it was all delicious. The mimosa options were good, I opted for the kiwi one; 'when in Rome'. I'd like to go back for dinner and see what Kiwi food is all about.

This place blew me away. Friendly and professional service, amazing food (we had a warm octopus salad with chorizo and chimichurri sauce and the roasted beets with lavendar whipped ricotta), and a sweet atmosphere. Will be coming back for more soon!
Great brunch spot, fresh food and amazing cappuccino!
I loved brunch. It was a lovely time.
1 of a kind place with great food and staff
Very tasty, with a quaint atmosphere. Food was well made.

A go-to place for brunch (cash only)- delicious with great service! Try the scones-these are literally the best scones I've ever tasted. My favorite brunch items include the seasonal omelet, if you're feeling savory and the chai-spiced french toast, if you're feeling sweet!

Chef Mark Simmons has done it again!  We just returned from another delicious dinner at Kiwiana.  What a treat!  Everything Chef Mark creates is incredible, and it’s no wonder our kids are constantly asking when they can go back for more.  We highly recommend Kiwiana for an excellent meal!
New Zealand restaurant with tasty options. Brunch is very good - pulled pork sliders and scones are great.  Cash only for brunch
Nice little place with a very friendly staff.

It has the feel that the owner opened a New Zealand restaurant due to the lack of a New Zealand restaurant in Park Slope. The food has nothing with NZ to do. It's fried American and not tasty.  The place has a feeling of a dictatorship, the workers are petrified from the boss. Very unfriendly vibe to it.  My friend got a poached egg brunch special, the egg came after 15minutes cooked through and through, like your boiled egg (not like a half boiled egg) would be cooked less, so he didn't eat it, and asked for the bill.  The charge was there, when asked to remove it, after 10 minutes of the staff running and whispering around, and when inquiring again, they said that the chef will come out to talk to us, a overly sweaty (thinking of what happens with all that dripping sweat in the kitchen..) chef comes out, and starts arguing;  Chef: did you eat the spinach? Costumer: no! Chef: did u eat the potatoes? Costumer: yes! Etc etc..  it was amusing, like a serious interrogation, and in the end only wanted to remove half the dishes costs. I was shocked but compassionate with the chefs tactics in a way, because the place was empty like a ghost town..

We had a lovely dinner here. The whitebait latkes were spectacular, as was the rack of lamb, and hurray for New Zealand chardonnay!

One of my favorite places to go for oysters and fried chicken.  The chicken is so crispy and goes well with their clove honey.  Their other dishes are also very elegant and tasy, but oysters, fried chicken and lamb chops are the way to go!

Walked by and saw the specials of warm octopus salad and a grilled pork chop written out front...that pulled us in.  Delicious fresh food - really enjoyed everything we ate.  Fresh, flavorful dishes...can't wait to go back for more.

Not bad but overrated and overpriced. I would recommend the fresh juice but nothing else seemed to be worth the cost. Maybe my expectations were too high because of the reviews but this place seemed just average to me.
Quick & friendly service, freshly made & tasty food. Must have the scones!
Good food, but small portions. The waitress was extremely fun and joyful.

Had great service and very yummy food at a Saturday brunch. It wasn't very full, but they were closing midday for a private event so that might have changed things. Was a bit surprised that brunch was cash only. The French toast was delicious. And my friend said her Eggs Benedict was quite yummy too.
went here for an early dinner special. the food was very well prepared

Great food, friendly staff. The fried chicken (with New Zealand-based spices) is worth fantasizing about. The yucca tater tots? Amazing. This small place is one of the great, underrated neighborhood spots.
New Zealand inspired food. Good for brunch. Can be a little bit noisy and busy
Very good food with mild Kiwi accent. (Other than serving anzac biscuits with the cheese plate, not sure what else was NZ related.)  Excellent service and pleasant atmosphere.
Amazing staff and owner ! Definitely a place to visit!
Fantastic. Love this place, the atmosphere is friendly, nice and open; the staff attentive and the food is phenomenal.
Very nice place. Good food and atmosphere.

I went here for brunch with my friend. I got the Kiwi burger and it was surprisingly delicious. My friend got the eggs benedict and he enjoyed it. Overall it was a good experience at the restaurant because the wait staff was nice.
Need to go back and try some more dishes but was not overly impressed with the selection. Prices seemed high for smaller portions, definitely high quality though.

Great brunch spot in park slope. Super friendly staff and attentive. Variety of brunch cocktails mixed with fresh fruit. Standouts are the kiwi and i went with the bloody mary. Could of used a bit more kick and tomato flavor but still satisfying. Nice options of specials and i went with the veggie omlette special. Fresh ingredients and the veggies were bursting with flavor especially the string beans and corn. Tasted like it was straight from the farm. Wonderful bratwurst that had a nice crisp and spice to it. Go for the scone as well. Fresh butter and buttery soft scone texture. The cherry compote accompanied it well. I'll be back again.

Beautifully plated and perfectly executed seasonal dishes. Most recent dish that I highly recommend was the braised beef short rib. Excellent curated wine list highlighting the New Zealand and Australian regions. Go for the Mt. Difficulty Roaring Meg Pinot Noir! Delish!
Lovely New Zealand experience in the heart of Park Slope.
small dark but friendly service .Excellent food.Made to feel welcome.One complaint is thst they are frequently booked for baby showers.But this is Park Slope.
Beautiful kiwi fusion food, fascinating and delicious cocktails (I had the Cheap Date), friendly service. Quaint, quirky, lovely.  Not cheap, but good value.

A great local farm to table restaurant with a New Zealand flare.  We had a great dinner and were never rushed even though it was a Friday night at peak times.  The food was so delicious, it's hard to pick one favorite dish.  If I had any complaint it may be that the bar was not fully stocked.
Nice place whith a lot of NZ beer choice.  Gastronomic and NZ specialties I guess, but a little expensive.

very rare you come across a small Gem in a high traffic area of Brooklyn, food is amazing and I had the most wonderful Pinot Noir to go along with my dinner, the name was Misha's High Note and it seemed that the wine was made for this style of food a must try! I will be a steady customer for sure
Quite possibly the best French toast I have ever had. Service was friendly, watermelon / mint-infused cocktail was quite tasty. A great first experience in the Slope.

A belated post, with the best of intentions.  I went to this event that was held in a retail store(don't recall what it was for), and they happened to be serving these divine hors d'oeuvres and amazingly delicious kiwi cocktails.  I took note of this restaurant with the intention of dining there.  Fast forward to a year later, and I'm planning a surprise engagement/wedding send-off brunch for my best friend and her husband.  I immediately recall that September night where I had filed Kiwiana into my foodie brain, and contacted the chef, Mr. Mark Simmons.  After some email correspondence, I worked out the date, pre-fixe price per head and custom menu(including unlimited drinks) for our party of close to 30.  Since it is a small space, we had the entire restaurant to ourselves for the duration of the event.  The staff was so helpful and generous with the time we spent there; I was thoroughly impressed. The scrumptious scones and the ribs were a delicious hit, as were the kiwi cocktails.  We were never rushed out; plenty of time was given to our guests of honor for mingling and creating memories.  When they ran out of the kiwi mimosas, they offered up regular ones down to the very last minute.  The chef came out to greet us afterwards which added a more personal touch.  Needless to say, the bride and groom were very happy and it was a very successful event.  I would definitely consider hosting another special day here.
Ghourri Smart Art

Visited for New Year's Eve dinner for the first time and will have to give this place a second chance. They changed the menu from what they advertised online, chowder instead of a tuna tartare and removing the lamb tongue that I was curious about. The food was delicious but the portions were tiny and I was still hungry when we left. The cocktails were pretty good but tended towards the sweeter side. I've heard good things about their brunch.

Went there for a baby shower with about 20 women.  That's a lot of women for one man to handle!  Connor was an excellent host, very attentive!  The mimosas were flowing.  Mango was by far the favorite.  Overall, the food was good but the beet pasta was a bit overpowering for some.  I had fried chicken.  It had a honey with truffle oil dipping sauce that was very tasty.  Kale slaw was delicious!

After hearing lots of good things about this place from friends and reviews, I was hoping to be delighted; alas the food and service was well below average.  Welcomed with a smile, but after the initial menu handout, we barely got the attention of the waiter/waitresses to order the food and the check.  Eggs Benedict whilst looking great, was totally let down down with what was meant to be hollandaise but in fact something that resembled whipped butter.  Rest of the dish seemed to have some good quality ingredients, but the hollandaise is what makes it.  I want to say i'll be back because of the reviews, but not in a rush.

Consistently good food at a reasonable price.  Friendly service -- chef Mark even comes out to check on things.  The decor is modeled after his grandma's kitchen, very different from the typical tin ceiling and brick wall look.  Brunch is fairly busy, but there seems to always be one open table, so somehow I never have to wait.  Try the pork sliders, peach and ricotta thing, or the lamb/beet/egg burger.  For dinner try the lamb -- it just falls off the bone.

This is a great place.  Excellent food, great service and nice decor.   We had our baby shower here and it turned out great.  If you are looking for a venue to hold a baby shower, private event or birthday party, look no further.
When we've run out of places to go we head to Kiwiana - it's here, it's pleasant enough and it's a change. The brunch is pretty good. Dinner is so-so. If you're a foodie brunch is your best bet.

Went to Kiwiana for an early dinner and caught the end of happy hour. The restaurant is beautifully decorated (what perplexing wallpaper!) with an attentive wait staff. The prices are a little over my every day budget, but are worth every penny! Try the Farmer's Daughter cocktail if they're still making it. I also highly recommend the lamb burger!
Great beers, good food but noisy
